addr="larsbirkedal">Lars Birkedal</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00OI</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:em>What is the relationship between <fr:tex>\mathsf {posCounter}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>\mathsf {negCounter}</fr:tex>?</fr:em></fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause><fr:p>They appear to be indistinguishable. <html:mark
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Indeed, they are “observationally equivalent”!</html:mark></fr:p><fr:tex
display="block">   \forall  \mathcal {C}{\mathopen {}\left  [-\right  ]\mathclose {}}\colon  \mathsf {Counter}\to  \mathsf {T}\,{\mathopen {}\left (\right )\mathclose {}}\mathpunct {.}   \mathcal {C}{\mathopen {}\left  [\mathsf {posCounter}\right  ]\mathclose {}} \mathord {\downarrow }   \Leftrightarrow    \mathcal {C}{\mathopen {}\left  [\mathsf {negCounter}\right  ]\mathclose {}} \mathord {\downarrow }  </fr:tex><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause><fr:p><fr:strong>Observational equivalence is an extremely weak property:</fr:strong> indistinguishability under observations of ground type only.<beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause>
 It would be great if we could instead deduce an absolute equation: <fr:tex
display="block">\color {red}\vdash  \mathsf {posCounter} \equiv  \mathsf {negCounter} \colon  \mathsf {Counter}</fr:tex> (No cheating: we want “standard” models <fr:em>without</fr:em> extensional collapse or logical relation.)</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
